<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06064129 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06064129 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  ROBBERY; ARREST; SAN-JOSE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Detective Sgt. Doug Bergtholdt did a double-take when he was checking policecomputers for the possible criminal background of a man charged Thursday withan attempted burglary in downtown San Jose.;    &quot;He was supposed to be incounty jail serving a six-month sentence for burglary,&quot; Bergtholdt said.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MAN DOING JAIL TIME ARRESTED IN BURGLARY  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The officer quickly called the Department of Correction to see howFlorentino Ramirez, 28, could have been picked up at 2:15 a.m. Wednesdayallegedly trying to pilfer the International Auto Repair on Almaden Expresswaywhen records showed he was behind bars.;    Ramirez was part of a publicservice program designed to reduce jail overcrowding. Each morning, theconvicted burglar had to check in at jail, Bergtholdt said, and work eighthours for the correctional department. But at night, he was allowed to go home.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  BETTY BARNACLE, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910304  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  133  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday March 4, 199100064129,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>